# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mocha-chai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] The BDD styles are `expect` and `should`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Both use the same chainable language to construct assertions, but they differ in the way an assertion is initially constructed.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Check out the Style Guide for a comparison.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] The following are provided as chainable getters to improve the readability of your assertions.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Negates all assertions that follow in the chain.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Just because you can negate any assertion with `.not` doesn’t mean you should.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] With great power comes great responsibility.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] It’s often best to assert that the one expected output was produced, rather than asserting that one of countless unexpected outputs wasn’t produced.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] See individual assertions for specific guidance.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Causes all `.equal`, `.include`, `.members`, `.keys`, and `.property` assertions that follow in the chain to use deep equality instead of strict (`===`) equality.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] See the `deep-eql` project page for info on the deep equality algorithm: https://github.com/chaijs/deep-eql.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Enables dot- and bracket-notation in all `.property` and `.include` assertions that follow in the chain.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] If `.` or `[]` are part of an actual property name, they can be escaped by adding two backslashes before them.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.nested` cannot be combined with `.own`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Causes all `.property` and `.include` assertions that follow in the chain to ignore inherited properties.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.own` cannot be combined with `.nested`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Causes all `.members` assertions that follow in the chain to require that members be in the same order.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When `.include` and `.ordered` are combined, the ordering begins at the start of both arrays.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Causes all `.keys` assertions that follow in the chain to only require that the target have at least one of the given keys.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] This is the opposite of `.all`, which requires that the target have all of the given keys.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] See the `.keys` doc for guidance on when to use `.any` or `.all`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Causes all `.keys` assertions that follow in the chain to require that the target have all of the given keys.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] This is the opposite of `.any`, which only requires that the target have at least one of the given keys.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Note that `.all` is used by default when neither `.all` nor `.any` are added earlier in the chain.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] However, it’s often best to add `.all` anyway because it improves readability.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Asserts that the target’s type is equal to the given string `type`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] See the `type-detect` project page for info on the type detection algorithm: https://github.com/chaijs/type-detect.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.a` supports objects that have a custom type set via `Symbol.toStringTag`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] It’s often best to use `.a` to check a target’s type before making more assertions on the same target.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] That way, you avoid unexpected behavior from any assertion that does different things based on the target’s type.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Add `.not` earlier in the chain to negate `.a`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] However, it’s often best to assert that the target is the expected type, rather than asserting that it isn’t one of many unexpected types.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.a` accepts an optional `msg` argument which is a custom error message to show when the assertion fails.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] The message can also be given as the second argument to `expect`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.a` can also be used as a language chain to improve the readability of your assertions.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] The alias `.an` can be used interchangeably with `.a`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target is a string, `.include` asserts that the given string `val` is a substring of the target.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target is an array, `.include` asserts that the given `val` is a member of the target.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target is an object, `.include` asserts that the given object `val`’s properties are a subset of the target’s properties.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target is a Set or WeakSet, `.include` asserts that the given `val` is a member of the target.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] SameValueZero equality algorithm is used.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target is a Map, `.include` asserts that the given `val` is one of the values of the target.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Because `.include` does different things based on the target’s type, it’s important to check the target’s type before using `.include`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] See the `.a` doc for info on testing a target’s type.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] By default, strict (`===`) equality is used to compare array members and object properties.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Add `.deep` earlier in the chain to use deep equality instead (WeakSet targets are not supported).
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] By default, all of the target’s properties are searched when working with objects.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] This includes properties that are inherited and/or non-enumerable.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Add `.own` earlier in the chain to exclude the target’s inherited properties from the search.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Note that a target object is always only searched for `val`’s own enumerable properties.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Add `.nested` earlier in the chain to enable dot- and bracket-notation when referencing nested properties.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.own` and `.nested` cannot be combined.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Add `.not` earlier in the chain to negate `.include`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] However, it’s dangerous to negate `.include` when the target is an object.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] The problem is that it creates uncertain expectations by asserting that the target object doesn’t have all of `val`’s key/value pairs but may or may not have some of them.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] It’s often best to identify the exact output that’s expected, and then write an assertion that only accepts that exact output.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target object isn’t even expected to have `val`’s keys, it’s often best to assert exactly that.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] When the target object is expected to have `val`’s keys, it’s often best to assert that each of the properties has its expected value, rather than asserting that each property doesn’t have one of many unexpected values.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.include` accepts an optional `msg` argument which is a custom error message to show when the assertion fails.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] `.include` can also be used as a language chain, causing all `.members` and `.keys` assertions that follow in the chain to require the target to be a superset of the expected set, rather than an identical set.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Note that `.members` ignores duplicates in the subset when `.include` is added.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Note that adding `.any` earlier in the chain causes the `.keys` assertion to ignore `.include`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] The aliases `.includes`, `.contain`, and `.contains` can be used interchangeably with `.include`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Asserts that the target is a truthy value (considered `true` in boolean context).
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] However, it’s often best to assert that the target is strictly (`===`) or deeply equal to its expected value.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p01] Add `.not` earlier in the chain to negate `.ok`.
