[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When the target is an object or array, keys can be provided as one or more string arguments, a single array argument, or a single object argument.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] In the latter case, only the keys in the given object matter; the values are ignored.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When the target is a map or set, each key must be provided as a separate argument.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Because `.keys` does different things based on the target’s type, it’s important to check the target’s type before using `.keys`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] By default, strict (`===`) equality is used to compare keys of maps and sets.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] By default, the target must have all of the given keys and no more.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Add `.any` earlier in the chain to only require that the target have at least one of the given keys.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Also, add `.not` earlier in the chain to negate `.keys`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] It’s often best to add `.any` when negating `.keys`, and to use `.all` when asserting `.keys` without negation.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When negating `.keys`, `.any` is preferred because `.not.any.keys` asserts exactly what’s expected of the output, whereas `.not.all.keys` creates uncertain expectations.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When asserting `.keys` without negation, `.all` is preferred because `.all.keys` asserts exactly what’s expected of the output, whereas `.any.keys` creates uncertain expectations.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Note that `.all` is used by default when neither `.all` nor `.any` appear earlier in the chain.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Add `.include` earlier in the chain to require that the target’s keys be a superset of the expected keys, rather than identical sets.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] However, if `.any` and `.include` are combined, only the `.any` takes effect.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] The alias `.key` can be used interchangeably with `.keys`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When no arguments are provided, `.throw` invokes the target function and asserts that an error is thrown.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When one argument is provided, and it’s an error constructor, `.throw` invokes the target function and asserts that an error is thrown that’s an instance of that error constructor.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When one argument is provided, and it’s an error instance, `.throw` invokes the target function and asserts that an error is thrown that’s strictly (`===`) equal to that error instance.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When one argument is provided, and it’s a string, `.throw` invokes the target function and asserts that an error is thrown with a message that contains that string.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When one argument is provided, and it’s a regular expression, `.throw` invokes the target function and asserts that an error is thrown with a message that matches that regular expression.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When two arguments are provided, and the first is an error instance or constructor, and the second is a string or regular expression, `.throw` invokes the function and asserts that an error is thrown that fulfills both conditions as described above.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Add `.not` earlier in the chain to negate `.throw`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] However, it’s dangerous to negate `.throw` when providing any arguments.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] The problem is that it creates uncertain expectations by asserting that the target either doesn’t throw an error, or that it throws an error but of a different type than the given type, or that it throws an error of the given type but with a message that doesn’t include the given string.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When the target isn’t expected to throw an error, it’s often best to assert exactly that.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When the target is expected to throw an error, it’s often best to assert that the error is of its expected type, and has a message that includes an expected string, rather than asserting that it doesn’t have one of many unexpected types, and doesn’t have a message that includes some string.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] `.throw` changes the target of any assertions that follow in the chain to be the error object that’s thrown.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] `.throw` accepts an optional `msg` argument which is a custom error message to show when the assertion fails.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When not providing two arguments, always use the second form.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Due to limitations in ES5, `.throw` may not always work as expected when using a transpiler such as Babel or TypeScript.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] In particular, it may produce unexpected results when subclassing the built-in `Error` object and then passing the subclassed constructor to `.throw`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Beware of some common mistakes when using the `throw` assertion.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] One common mistake is to accidentally invoke the function yourself instead of letting the `throw` assertion invoke the function for you.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] For example, when testing if a function named `fn` throws, provide `fn` instead of `fn()` as the target for the assertion.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] If you need to assert that your function `fn` throws when passed certain arguments, then wrap a call to `fn` inside of another function.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Another common mistake is to provide an object method (or any stand-alone function that relies on `this`) as the target of the assertion.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Doing so is problematic because the `this` context will be lost when the function is invoked by `.throw`; there’s no way for it to know what `this` is supposed to be.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] One solution is to wrap the method or function call inside of another function.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] Finally, it’s worth mentioning that it’s a best practice in JavaScript to only throw `Error` and derivatives of `Error` such as `ReferenceError`, `TypeError`, and user-defined objects that extend `Error`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] No other type of value will generate a stack trace when initialized.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] With that said, the `throw` assertion does technically support any type of value being thrown, not just `Error` and its derivatives.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] The aliases `.throws` and `.Throw` can be used interchangeably with `.throw`.
[src:mocha-chai/api-bdd-p02] When the target is a non-function object, `.respondTo` asserts that the target has a method with the given name `method`.
