[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:mocha-chai/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:mocha-chai/guide] We are glad that you have decided to give Chai.js a try!
[src:mocha-chai/guide] If this is your first visit, get acquainted with the basics, such as installation and our included assertion styles.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] After you have a solid knowledge of what is included in Chai, the next step is learning how to extend Chai through plugins.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] Chai is infinitely more powerful than what is included, limited only by what you want to achieve.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] The Plugin API is also intended as a way to simplify testing by providing users a way to encapsulate common assertions for repeat use.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] When creating a Chai plugin, it’s possible to expose globals that can be used across multiple files.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] In certain situations the `use(..)` function could be called multiple times with your plugin.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] For a lot of plugins this won’t be a issue but it’s considered best practise to check if the plugin has been applied already.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] Here’s a contrived example of how you might implement a check in your plugin but the actual implementation is left up to the plugin author.
[src:mocha-chai/guide] By following these guidelines, you can create Chai plugins that are easy to use and maintain.
[src:mocha-chai/mochajs-org] Mocha is a feature-rich JavaScript test framework running on Node.js and in the browser, making asynchronous testing *straightforward* and *fun*.
[src:mocha-chai/mochajs-org] Mocha tests run serially, allowing for flexible and accurate reporting, while mapping uncaught exceptions to the correct test cases.
[src:mocha-chai/mochajs-org] Ask your manager or marketing team if they’d help support our project.
